{"title_page": "Ashley Bloomfield", "text_new": "{{short description|New Zealand director-general of public health}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Ashley Bloomfield\n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year with {{Birth year and age|YYYY}} unless the exact date is already widely published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. For people who have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = New Zealander\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Director-General of Health\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Ashley Bloomfield''' is the chief executive of the New Zealand [[Ministry of Health (New Zealand)|Ministry of Health]] and the country's Director-General of Health. He has been the public-facing health specialist fronting the media on the country's [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Zealand|coronavirus pandemic]] on behalf of the government, fronting the first press conference on 27 January 2020.\n\n==Career== \nBloomfield, now 54, grew up in Tawa and was educated at Scots College, where he was head prefect.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12324032 |title= Ashley Bloomfield's rise to the top - the inside story |publisher= New Zealand Herald  |date=1 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nBloomfield graduated from the [[University of Auckland]] in medicine in 1990.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Thomas|first=Rachel|url=https://thespinoff.co.nz/science/28-03-2020/the-face-of-the-covid-19-response-who-is-ashley-bloomfield/|title=The face of the Covid-19 response: Who is Ashley Bloomfield?|date=28 March 2020|work=The Spinoff|access-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nHe had several years of clinical work and from 1996<ref name=\"Stuff bio\" /> specialised in public health medicine,<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.odt.co.nz/opinion/editorial/cometh-hour%E2%80%A6|title=Cometh the hour\u2026|date=21 March 2020|work=Otago Daily Times|access-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> concentrating on non-communicable disease.<ref name=\"MoH introduction\" /> Between 2004 and 2006, Bloomfield was the Ministry of Health's acting director of public health.<ref>{{cite news |title=Check for Sars symptoms, doctors told |url= https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=3563153 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |date=28 April 2004 | first=Renee |last=Kiriona}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Bird flu campaign to target 1.4m households |url= https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10364209 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |date=18 January 2006 |first1=Kiong |last1=Errol |first2=Martin |last2= Johnston }}</ref> From 2006 to 2010, he was the ministry's chief public health adviser.<ref name=\"Stuff bio\" />\n\nFrom late 2010 to late 2011, he was based at the [[World Health Organization]] in [[Geneva]] to work on non-communicable disease prevention and control with a global focus.<ref name=\"MoH introduction\">{{cite web |title=Introducing Ashley Bloomfield |url= https://www.health.govt.nz/news-media/news-items/introducing-ashley-bloomfield |publisher=[[Ministry of Health (New Zealand)|Ministry of Health]] |accessdate=18 March 2020 |date=13 June 2018}}</ref> From 2012 to 2015, he held leading positions across district health boards with [[Capital & Coast District Health Board|Capital & Coast District]], [[Hutt Valley District Health Board|Hutt Valley]], and [[Wairarapa District Health Board|Wairarapa]]. From 2015 to 2018, Bloomfield was chief executive at Hutt Valley District Health Board.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.health.govt.nz/about-ministry/leadership-ministry/executive-leadership-team#ashley|title=Dr Ashley Bloomfield: Director-General of Health and Chief Executive|last=|first=|date=25 November 2019|website=Ministry of Health Manat\u016b Hauoa|publisher=New Zealand Government|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> In the first half of 2018, Bloomfield was seconded to the [[Capital & Coast District Health Board]] where he was interim chief executive. Since June 2018, he has been the chief executive of the country's Ministry of Health and the country's Director-General of Health.<ref name=\"MoH introduction\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=Fisher|first=David|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12324032|title=Covid 19 coronavirus: The inside story of Ashley Bloomfield's rise to an 'utterly career defining' fight against the killer coronavirus|date=2020-04-10|work=NZ Herald|access-date=2020-04-10|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200410200754/https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12324032|archive-date=2020-04-10|language=en-NZ|issn=1170-0777}}</ref> Since he started as the ministry's CE, he has taken leadership training at [[Sa\u00efd Business School]] at the [[University of Oxford]].<ref name=\"Stuff bio\">{{cite news |last1=Macdonald |first1=Nikki |title=Coronavirus: Ashley Bloomfield is the face of NZ's virus defence |url= https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/120071359/coronavirus-ashley-bloomfield-is-the-face-of-nzs-pandemic-response |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nColleagues describe Bloomfield as \"measured, methodical, calm and sensible\".<ref name=\"Stuff bio\" /> Former health reporter Tess Nichol, writing for the American online magazine ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'', described him as \"New Zealand\u2019s current obsession, an unlikely heartthrob, a mild-mannered health care hero\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nichol |first1=Tess |title=The Extremely Competent, Somewhat Boring Civil Servant Who Has New Zealanders\u2019 Hearts Aflutter |url= https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/04/new-zealand-covid-19-coronavirus-ashley-bloomfield.html |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Coronavirus pandemic in New Zealand}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bloomfield, Ashley}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Auckland alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Sa\u00efd Business School]]\n[[Category:New Zealand public servants]]\n[[Category:New Zealand public health doctors]]\n[[Category:21st-century New Zealand medical doctors]]\n[[Category:21st-century New Zealand public servants]]\n[[Category:People educated at Scots College, Wellington]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|New Zealand director-general of public health}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Ashley Bloomfield\n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year with {{Birth year and age|YYYY}} unless the exact date is already widely published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. For people who have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = New Zealander\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Director-General of Health\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Ashley Bloomfield''' is the chief executive of the New Zealand [[Ministry of Health (New Zealand)|Ministry of Health]] and the country's Director-General of Health. He has been the public-facing health specialist fronting the media on the country's [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Zealand|coronavirus pandemic]] on behalf of the government, fronting the first press conference on 27 January 2020.\n\n==Career==\nBloomfield graduated from the [[University of Auckland]] in medicine in 1990.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Thomas|first=Rachel|url=https://thespinoff.co.nz/science/28-03-2020/the-face-of-the-covid-19-response-who-is-ashley-bloomfield/|title=The face of the Covid-19 response: Who is Ashley Bloomfield?|date=28 March 2020|work=The Spinoff|access-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He had several years of clinical work and from 1996<ref name=\"Stuff bio\" /> specialised in public health medicine,<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.odt.co.nz/opinion/editorial/cometh-hour%E2%80%A6|title=Cometh the hour\u2026|date=21 March 2020|work=Otago Daily Times|access-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> concentrating on non-communicable disease.<ref name=\"MoH introduction\" /> Between 2004 and 2006, Bloomfield was the Ministry of Health's acting director of public health.<ref>{{cite news |title=Check for Sars symptoms, doctors told |url= https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=3563153 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |date=28 April 2004 | first=Renee |last=Kiriona}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Bird flu campaign to target 1.4m households |url= https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10364209 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |date=18 January 2006 |first1=Kiong |last1=Errol |first2=Martin |last2= Johnston }}</ref> From 2006 to 2010, he was the ministry's chief public health adviser.<ref name=\"Stuff bio\" />\n\nFrom late 2010 to late 2011, he was based at the [[World Health Organization]] in [[Geneva]] to work on non-communicable disease prevention and control with a global focus.<ref name=\"MoH introduction\">{{cite web |title=Introducing Ashley Bloomfield |url= https://www.health.govt.nz/news-media/news-items/introducing-ashley-bloomfield |publisher=[[Ministry of Health (New Zealand)|Ministry of Health]] |accessdate=18 March 2020 |date=13 June 2018}}</ref> From 2012 to 2015, he held leading positions across district health boards with [[Capital & Coast District Health Board|Capital & Coast District]], [[Hutt Valley District Health Board|Hutt Valley]], and [[Wairarapa District Health Board|Wairarapa]]. From 2015 to 2018, Bloomfield was chief executive at Hutt Valley District Health Board.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.health.govt.nz/about-ministry/leadership-ministry/executive-leadership-team#ashley|title=Dr Ashley Bloomfield: Director-General of Health and Chief Executive|last=|first=|date=25 November 2019|website=Ministry of Health Manat\u016b Hauoa|publisher=New Zealand Government|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> In the first half of 2018, Bloomfield was seconded to the [[Capital & Coast District Health Board]] where he was interim chief executive. Since June 2018, he has been the chief executive of the country's Ministry of Health and the country's Director-General of Health.<ref name=\"MoH introduction\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=Fisher|first=David|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12324032|title=Covid 19 coronavirus: The inside story of Ashley Bloomfield's rise to an 'utterly career defining' fight against the killer coronavirus|date=2020-04-10|work=NZ Herald|access-date=2020-04-10|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200410200754/https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12324032|archive-date=2020-04-10|language=en-NZ|issn=1170-0777}}</ref> Since he started as the ministry's CE, he has taken leadership training at [[Sa\u00efd Business School]] at the [[University of Oxford]].<ref name=\"Stuff bio\">{{cite news |last1=Macdonald |first1=Nikki |title=Coronavirus: Ashley Bloomfield is the face of NZ's virus defence |url= https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/120071359/coronavirus-ashley-bloomfield-is-the-face-of-nzs-pandemic-response |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nColleagues describe Bloomfield as \"measured, methodical, calm and sensible\".<ref name=\"Stuff bio\" /> Former health reporter Tess Nichol, writing for the American online magazine ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'', described him as \"New Zealand\u2019s current obsession, an unlikely heartthrob, a mild-mannered health care hero\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nichol |first1=Tess |title=The Extremely Competent, Somewhat Boring Civil Servant Who Has New Zealanders\u2019 Hearts Aflutter |url= https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/04/new-zealand-covid-19-coronavirus-ashley-bloomfield.html |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Coronavirus pandemic in New Zealand}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bloomfield, Ashley}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Auckland alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Sa\u00efd Business School]]\n[[Category:New Zealand public servants]]\n[[Category:New Zealand public health doctors]]\n[[Category:21st-century New Zealand medical doctors]]\n[[Category:21st-century New Zealand public servants]]\n[[Category:People educated at Scots College, Wellington]]\n", "name_user": "Hugo999", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ashley_Bloomfield"}
{"title_page": "Forever (Charli XCX song)", "text_new": "{{short description|2020 single by Charli XCX}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name        = Forever\n| type        = single\n| cover       = Charli XCX - Forever.jpg\n| border = yes\n| caption = Designed by Regards Coupables\n| artist      = [[Charli XCX]]\n| album       = [[How I'm Feeling Now]]\n| released    = {{start date|2020|04|09|df=yes}}\n| recorded    = 6\u20138 April 2020<ref name= \"Pitchfork\">{{cite web |title=Listen to Charli XCX's New Song \"forever\"|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/listen-to-charli-xcx-new-song-forever/?verso=true|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|accessdate= 9 April 2020}}</ref>\n| format      =\n* [[Music download|Digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| genre       =\n*[[Pop music|Pop]]<ref name=\"spin\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2020/04/charli-xcx-shares-forever-from-upcoming-quarantine-album/|title=Charli XCX Shares 'Forever' From Upcoming Quarantine Album|date=9 April 2020|website=Spin}}</ref>\n*[[synth-pop]]<ref name=\"nme\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/charli-xcx-new-single-forever-2644319|title=Listen to Charli XCX's new self-isolation single 'Forever'|date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n| length      = {{duration|m=4|s=3}}\n| label       = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n| writer      = \n* [[Charli XCX|Charlotte Aitchison]]\n* [[A. G. Cook|Alexander Guy Cook]]\n* [[BJ Burton]]\n| producer    = \n* [[A. G. Cook]] \n* [[BJ Burton]]\n| prev_title = Bricks\n| prev_year  = 2019\n| next_title = \n| next_year  = \n| misc       = {{External music video|1={{YouTube|1O9xP4g8zfU|\"Forever\"}}|header=Audio video|type=single}}\n{{Extra album cover\n| header = Apple Music cover\n| type = single\n| cover = Charli XCX Forever Cover Art - Caroline Polachek.jpg\n| border = yes\n| caption = Designed by Caroline Polachek\n}}\n{{Extra album cover\n| header = Spotify cover\n| type = single\n| cover = Charli XCX- Forever Spotfiy cover.jpg\n| border = yes\n| caption = Designed by Seth Bogart\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Forever'''\" (stylized in [[Letter case#All lowercase|all lowercase]]) is a song written and recorded by British singer [[Charli XCX]] from her upcoming fourth album ''[[How I'm Feeling Now]]'' (2020). Charli XCX produced the song with [[A. G. Cook]] and [[BJ Burton]], and it was released on 9 April 2020, by [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]] as the lead single from the album. \"Forever\" is a [[Pop music|pop]] and [[synth-pop]] song that features [[dark wave]] and [[Electronic music|electronic]] influences.\n\n==Background and release==\nOn 7 April 2020, Charli XCX shared snippets of \"Forever\" on social media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/charli-xcx-new-song-forever-clip-album-2642649|title=Listen to a clip of Charli XCX\u2019s new song 'Forever' from upcoming quarantine album|date=7 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020|website=[[NME]]|author=Tom Skinner}}</ref> On 8 April 2020, Charli XCX uploaded three photos of herself, shot by her boyfriend, to her [[Instagram]] and [[Twitter]] account and asked fans to vote for one photo to be the cover. On 9 April 2020, Charli XCX announced that \"Forever\" would be released at 07:30 PM [[British Summer Time|BST]] / 11:30 AM [[Pacific Standard Time|PST]] and premiere on [[BBC Radio 1]] as [[Annie Mac]]'s Hottest Record in the World.<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=charli_xcx |number=1248287541306036225 |title=\ud83d\udc93 FOREVER DROPS AT 7.30PM BST/11:30AM PST PREMIERING AS HOTTEST RECORD ON @ANNIEMAC ON @BBCR1!!!!! ARTWORK BY @SETHBOGARTOK!!! 2 MORE OFFICIAL ARTWORKS TO COME LATER IN THE DAY \ud83d\udc93 THANK YOU FOR HELPING ME CREATE THE FIRST SONG FROM \"HOW I\u2019M FEELING NOW\" \ud83d\udc93 |date=9 April 2020 |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> She also announced three official artworks for the single were commissioned.<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=charli_xcx |number=1248043315951370240 |title=fyi i am making multiple official artworks for every song I release before the album, maybe even multiple album covers too. the \"forever\" artwork will be based of the photo we selected together and will be visually interpreted by @SethBogartOK @carolineplz and @regardscoupable \ud83d\udc93 |date=8 April 2020 |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> One version was created by American artist [[Seth Bogart (artist)|Seth Bogart]] and used on [[Spotify]]; one version by French artist Regards Coupables, used on [[YouTube]] and [[Amazon Music]]<ref>{{cite web |title=forever - Single by Charli XCX on Amazon Music |url=https://music.amazon.com/albums/B086WQ21WX |website=[[Amazon Music]]|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>; and one version by American singer-songwriter [[Caroline Polachek]], used on [[Apple Music]].\n\n==Composition==\n\"Forever\" was written by Charli XCX and produced by [[A. G. Cook]] and [[BJ Burton]]. It runs for four minutes and three seconds.<ref name= \"Spotify\">{{cite web |title=forever - Single by Charli XCX on Spotify|url=https://open.spotify.com/album/0yl0sfY3TM3EDLPWghBkfc|website=[[Spotify]]|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> Musically, it is a [[Pop music|pop]]<ref name=\"spin\"/> and [[synth-pop]]<ref name=\"nme\"/> song that features [[dark wave]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/music/charli-xcx/forever/|title=Charli XCX Returns to the Raves on \"Forever,\" The First Track From how i'm feeling now|date=9 April 2020|website=pastemagazine.com}}</ref> and [[Electronic music|electronic]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euphoriazine.com/blog/2020/04/new-music/tracks-charli-xcx-forever/|title=Charli XCX - Forever|date=9 April 2020}}</ref> influences.\n\n==Credits and personnel==\nCredits adapted from [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/136824746|title=Credits / forever / Charli XCX \u2013 TIDAL|website=[[Tidal (service)]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n* [[Charli XCX]] \u2013 vocals, songwriting, backing vocals\n* [[A. G. Cook]] \u2013 production, songwriting, drum programming, programming, synthesizer, vocal production, xylophone\n* [[BJ Burton]] \u2013 production, songwriting, drum programming, programming, synthesizer, vocal production\n* Geoff Swan \u2013 mixing\n* Stuart Hawkes \u2013 mastering\n* Niko Battistini \u2013 assistant mix engineer\n\n==Release history==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n! scope=\"col\" | Region\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Format\n! scope=\"col\" | Label\n! scope=\"col\" | {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Various\n| 9 April 2020\n| {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n| <ref name= \"Apple Music\">{{cite web |title=forever - Single by Charli XCX on Apple Music|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/forever-single/1506988314|website=[[Apple Music]]|accessdate= 9 April 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Charli XCX}}\n\n[[Category:2020 singles]]\n[[Category:2020 songs]]\n[[Category:Charli XCX songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Charli XCX]]\n\n{{2020s-single-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2020 single by Charli XCX}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name        = Forever\n| type        = single\n| cover       = Charli XCX - Forever.jpg\n| border = yes\n| caption = Designed by Regards Coupables\n| artist      = [[Charli XCX]]\n| album       = [[How I'm Feeling Now]]\n| released    = {{start date|2020|04|09|df=yes}}\n| recorded    = 6\u20138 April 2020<ref name= \"Pitchfork\">{{cite web |title=Listen to Charli XCX's New Song \"forever\"|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/listen-to-charli-xcx-new-song-forever/?verso=true|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|accessdate= 9 April 2020}}</ref>\n| format      =\n* [[Music download|Digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| genre       =\n*[[Pop music|Pop]]<ref name=\"spin\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2020/04/charli-xcx-shares-forever-from-upcoming-quarantine-album/|title=Charli XCX Shares 'Forever' From Upcoming Quarantine Album|date=9 April 2020|website=Spin}}</ref>\n*[[synth-pop]]<ref name=\"nme\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/charli-xcx-new-single-forever-2644319|title=Listen to Charli XCX's new self-isolation single 'Forever'|date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n| length      = {{duration|m=4|s=3}}\n| label       = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n| writer      = \n* [[Charli XCX|Charlotte Aitchison]]\n* [[A. G. Cook|Alexander Guy Cook]]\n* [[BJ Burton]]\n| producer    = \n* [[A. G. Cook]] \n* BJ Burton\n| prev_title = Bricks\n| prev_year  = 2019\n| next_title = \n| next_year  = \n| misc       = {{External music video|1={{YouTube|1O9xP4g8zfU|\"Forever\"}}|header=Audio video|type=single}}\n{{Extra album cover\n| header = Apple Music cover\n| type = single\n| cover = Charli XCX Forever Cover Art - Caroline Polachek.jpg\n| border = yes\n| caption = Designed by Caroline Polachek\n}}\n{{Extra album cover\n| header = Spotify cover\n| type = single\n| cover = Charli XCX- Forever Spotfiy cover.jpg\n| border = yes\n| caption = Designed by Seth Bogart\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Forever'''\" (stylized in [[Letter case#All lowercase|all lowercase]]) is a song written and recorded by British singer [[Charli XCX]] from her upcoming fourth album ''[[How I'm Feeling Now]]'' (2020). Charli XCX produced the song with [[A. G. Cook]] and [[BJ Burton]], and it was released on 9 April 2020, by [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]] as the lead single from the album. \"Forever\" is a [[Pop music|pop]] and [[synth-pop]] song that features [[dark wave]] and [[Electronic music|electronic]] influences.\n\n==Background and release==\nOn 7 April 2020, Charli XCX shared snippets of \"Forever\" on social media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/charli-xcx-new-song-forever-clip-album-2642649|title=Listen to a clip of Charli XCX\u2019s new song 'Forever' from upcoming quarantine album|date=7 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020|website=[[NME]]|author=Tom Skinner}}</ref> On 8 April 2020, Charli XCX uploaded three photos of herself, shot by her boyfriend, to her [[Instagram]] and [[Twitter]] account and asked fans to vote for one photo to be the cover. On 9 April 2020, Charli XCX announced that \"Forever\" would be released at 07:30 PM [[British Summer Time|BST]] / 11:30 AM [[Pacific Standard Time|PST]] and premiere on [[BBC Radio 1]] as [[Annie Mac]]'s Hottest Record in the World.<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=charli_xcx |number=1248287541306036225 |title=\ud83d\udc93 FOREVER DROPS AT 7.30PM BST/11:30AM PST PREMIERING AS HOTTEST RECORD ON @ANNIEMAC ON @BBCR1!!!!! ARTWORK BY @SETHBOGARTOK!!! 2 MORE OFFICIAL ARTWORKS TO COME LATER IN THE DAY \ud83d\udc93 THANK YOU FOR HELPING ME CREATE THE FIRST SONG FROM \"HOW I\u2019M FEELING NOW\" \ud83d\udc93 |date=9 April 2020 |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> She also announced three official artworks for the single were commissioned.<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=charli_xcx |number=1248043315951370240 |title=fyi i am making multiple official artworks for every song I release before the album, maybe even multiple album covers too. the \"forever\" artwork will be based of the photo we selected together and will be visually interpreted by @SethBogartOK @carolineplz and @regardscoupable \ud83d\udc93 |date=8 April 2020 |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> One version was created by American artist [[Seth Bogart (artist)|Seth Bogart]] and used on [[Spotify]]; one version by French artist Regards Coupables, used on [[YouTube]] and [[Amazon Music]]<ref>{{cite web |title=forever - Single by Charli XCX on Amazon Music |url=https://music.amazon.com/albums/B086WQ21WX |website=[[Amazon Music]]|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>; and one version by American singer-songwriter [[Caroline Polachek]], used on [[Apple Music]].\n\n==Composition==\n\"Forever\" was written by Charli XCX and produced by [[A. G. Cook]] and [[BJ Burton]]. It runs for four minutes and three seconds.<ref name= \"Spotify\">{{cite web |title=forever - Single by Charli XCX on Spotify|url=https://open.spotify.com/album/0yl0sfY3TM3EDLPWghBkfc|website=[[Spotify]]|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> Musically, it is a [[Pop music|pop]]<ref name=\"spin\"/> and [[synth-pop]]<ref name=\"nme\"/> song that features [[dark wave]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/music/charli-xcx/forever/|title=Charli XCX Returns to the Raves on \"Forever,\" The First Track From how i'm feeling now|date=9 April 2020|website=pastemagazine.com}}</ref> and [[Electronic music|electronic]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euphoriazine.com/blog/2020/04/new-music/tracks-charli-xcx-forever/|title=Charli XCX - Forever|date=9 April 2020}}</ref> influences.\n\n==Credits and personnel==\nCredits adapted from [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/136824746|title=Credits / forever / Charli XCX \u2013 TIDAL|website=[[Tidal (service)]]|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n* [[Charli XCX]] \u2013 vocals, songwriting, backing vocals\n* [[A. G. Cook]] \u2013 production, songwriting, drum programming, programming, synthesizer, vocal production, xylophone\n* [[BJ Burton]] \u2013 production, songwriting, drum programming, programming, synthesizer, vocal production\n* Geoff Swan \u2013 mixing\n* Stuart Hawkes \u2013 mastering\n* Niko Battistini \u2013 assistant mix engineer\n\n==Release history==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n! scope=\"col\" | Region\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Format\n! scope=\"col\" | Label\n! scope=\"col\" | {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Various\n| 9 April 2020\n| {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n| <ref name= \"Apple Music\">{{cite web |title=forever - Single by Charli XCX on Apple Music|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/forever-single/1506988314|website=[[Apple Music]]|accessdate= 9 April 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Charli XCX}}\n\n[[Category:2020 singles]]\n[[Category:2020 songs]]\n[[Category:Charli XCX songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Charli XCX]]\n\n{{2020s-single-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Harveyw34", "label": "safe", "comment": "linked in pages", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forever_(Charli_XCX_song)"}
{"title_page": "VIPKid", "text_new": "{{short description|China-based online teaching and educational company}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = VIPKid\n| logo = File:VIPKID Logo.png\n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| industry = {{unbulleted list\n | [[Education]], [[Educational technology|Educational technology services]]\n}}\n| founded = {{Start date and age|2013|10}}\n| founders = [[Cindy Mi]] <br>\n}}\n'''VIPKid''', also known as '''VIPKID''', is an [[Educational technology|online teaching]] and educational company.\n\n==History==\nFounded in 2013 and formally launched in 2014 by [[Cindy Mi]], the VIPKid platform connects paying students with teachers in the United States and Canada.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/02/business/new-work-summit-excerpts.html|title=Excerpts From the New Work Summit|date=2019-03-02|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-08-14|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/Business%20Wire/7909cdbd72e941c1b842ec25406e0582|title=VIPKid Joins BrandZ\u2019s Top 100 Most Valuable Chinese Brands Five Years After Its Founding|date=2019-05-06|website=AP NEWS|access-date=2019-08-14}}</ref> VIPKid\u2019s online-classroom portal enables students to receive 25-minute English language lessons from fluent English-speaking teachers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.roadaffair.com/ultimate-guide-teaching-english-with-vipkid/|title=The Ultimate Guide to Teaching English with VIPKID|date=2019-01-23|website=Road Affair|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.vipkid.com.cn/why-does-vipkid-use-common-core/|title=Why does VIPKID use Common Core|last=VIPKID|date=2017-12-28|website=VIPKID Teacher Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-14}}</ref> Students and teachers communicate via a [[video chat]] platform.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cdmd.cnki.com.cn/Article/CDMD-10151-1018287717.htm|title=VIPKID\u57f9\u8bad\u516c\u53f8\u53d1\u5c55\u7b56\u7565\u7814\u7a76--\u300a\u5927\u8fde\u6d77\u4e8b\u5927\u5b66\u300b2018\u5e74\u7855\u58eb\u8bba\u6587|website=cdmd.cnki.com.cn|access-date=2019-02-05}}</ref>  \n\nIn 2017, VIPKid launched a new service to teach [[Mandarin Chinese|Mandarin]] to students 5 to 12 years-old, called Lingo Bus.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/a/201808/28/WS5b84b9e8a310add14f388287.html|title=Lingo Bus extends Mandarin learning offering - Chinadaily.com.cn|last=\u8463\u5fd7\u6210|website=www.chinadaily.com.cn|access-date=2019-02-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://technode.com/2018/08/30/big-chinese-abroad/|title=\"Big Chinese\" is edtech's next big thing, but its path overseas is unclear \u00b7 TechNode|date=2018-08-30|website=TechNode|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-05}}</ref> \n\nIn 2017, the company reported that it had raised $200 million in initial series funding,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-08-23/china-s-vipkid-raises-200-million-from-tencent-sequoia-china|title=China's VIPKid Is Said to Raise Funds at $1.5 Billion Valuation}}</ref> and in April 2018 raised an additional $500 million in series D+ funding.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20180621005418/en/VIPKID-Raises-500-Million-Series-Financing-Led|title=VIPKID Raises $500 Million in Series D+ Financing, Led by Coatue Management, Tencent, Sequoia Capital and Yunfeng Capital|date=2018-06-21|website=www.businesswire.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-05}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2018/06/21/chinas-vipkid-which-links-native-english-speakers-with-online-learners-raises-another-500m-reportedly-at-3b-valuation/|title=China\u2019s VIPKID, which links English tutors with online learners, raises $500M at $3B+ valuation|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-05}}</ref> Combined, this amount equated VIPKID's valuation to $3 billion.<ref name=\":3\" /> As of November 2018, the company reported having 60,000 teachers contracted to teach 500,000 students.\n\nIn March 2019, VIPKid fired two American teachers for discussing the [[1989 Tiananmen Square protests]] and [[Taiwan]] with their students in China.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Steinberg |first1=Julie |title=Chinese Education Startup Puts Western Teachers on Notice |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-education-startup-puts-western-teachers-on-notice-11553160602 |website=WSJ |date=March 21, 2019}}</ref> Teachers have also reported witnessing child abuse when teaching lessons, but they found little recourse to report such issues.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/story/when-online-teaching-job-becomes-window-child-abuse/|title=When an Online Teaching Job Becomes a Window into Child Abuse|work=Wired|access-date=2019-11-19|language=en|issn=1059-1028}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, VIPKid hosted the Journey Conference in Las Vegas where educators and students conferred on the topic of [[distance education]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news3lv.com/news/local/journey-conference-brings-teachers-from-around-the-nation-to-las-vegas-valley|title=Journey Conference brings teachers from around the nation to Las Vegas valley|last=Miller|first=Cody|date=2019-07-13|website=KSNV|access-date=2019-08-23}}</ref>\n== COVID-19 pandemic ==\n{{See also|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nIn February 2020,<!--Assuming it's February from the date the source was published.--> VIPKid donated 1.5 million English and math classes to affected students from the [[COVID-19 pandemic]]. Students in the city of Wuhan, Hubei Province, and children of medical workers were given priority for free classes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://netnebraska.org/article/news/1209222/nebraskans-see-boost-english-language-classes-chinese-kids-stay-home|title=Nebraskans See Boost In English Language Classes As Chinese Kids Stay Home {{!}} netnebraska.org|last=Costello|first=Becca|last2=News|first2=N. E. T.|website=netnebraska.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n== See a